This trend advances Iranian female empowerment, since it is often the case that women are coerced into staying in or remaining married to bad marriages, and thus exerting their rights helps them to escape an oppressive situation.

Additionally, the more women who claim divorce as their right, the more the stigma surrounding divorce falls away. Social conventions in Iran do say that women are largely to blame for the buckles in a marriage, but it is cultural norms more than religious ones that keep this notion alive. Even the Shi’ite patriarchal framework that governs Iranian society has aspects of the feminism embedded within it, since the religion permits women to hold property and file for divorce if they choose. Furthermore, in Iranian culture the involvement of women is relatively equal during things such as household maintenance.
